re up to the formation of the polis in the late eighth century B.C. He demonstrates that Greek society was already stratified well before that date and that the distinction between an elite and other classes was well developed. Thalmann concentrates on the representation of slaves and on the dynamics of competition and family structure in the contest of the bow to interpret the Odyssey-and, implicitly, epic poetry generally-as an intervention in the conflicts that surrounded the birth of the polis. In the interests of the aristocracy, the poem appropriates a traditional cultural paradigm, enshrined in the story of the Hero's return. The distortions of dark-age reality, he maintains, should form the basis of an historicizing reading of the poem.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 4aFolklore. 4aPoetry & Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package Archivez978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173899940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501738999423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501738999.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  COR eBook Package Archive  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK